{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17472818","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17472818"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:01:23+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:01:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1555"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1555","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1555"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.22,0.22,0.12,0.38]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1555"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107939"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1555","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1555"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1555"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90357"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"826"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17665"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40262"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42340"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44054"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107939","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107939"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA five-year-old boy presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-day history of worsening eczema that is not responding to his usual treatments. He has a history of atopic dermatitis since infancy but no other medical conditions. He does not take any regular medications except for moisturiser and intermittent topical steroids. His immunisations are up to date.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There are grouped vesiculopustular lesions with punched-out ulcerated papules distributed across his trunk and limbs (Image). The lesions are intensely pruritic and painful. There is no facial or ocular involvement.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Admit for intravenous antibiotics","Oral antibiotics with outpatient follow-up","Topical steroid cream","Admit for intravenous antivirals","Oral antivirals with outpatient follow-up"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with eczema herpeticum, which is caused by secondary infection of atopic dermatitis with \u003Cem\u003EHerpes simplex virus\u003C/em\u003E type 1 or 2. The characteristic findings include grouped vesiculopustular lesions with punched-out ulceration, pain, and rapid progression.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral antivirals with outpatient follow-up\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate management for an otherwise well child. As per therapeutic guidelines, management is now: aciclovir 10 mg/kg, up to 200 mg, orally 5 times daily for 5 to 7 days. These are given irrespective of the time since onset. Oral aciclovir is the standard treatment. This approach has reduced the need for hospital admission in uncomplicated cases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdmit for intravenous antibiotics\u003C/strong\u003E would be indicated if the patient showed signs of systemic illness or sepsis, which are not present in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral antibiotics\u003C/strong\u003E may be needed if there is evidence of secondary bacterial infection with yellow crusting, but addressing the viral infection is the priority.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdmit for intravenous antivirals\u003C/strong\u003E would be necessary if there was extensive disease, systemic symptoms, or immunocompromise, none of which are present here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical steroid cream\u003C/strong\u003E should be avoided in the acute phase as it may worsen the viral infection. Most dermatologists recommend waiting at least 48 hours after starting antiviral therapy before resuming topical steroids.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Eczema herpeticum is a serious secondary infection of eczema by Herpes simplex virus requiring prompt antiviral therapy.","Oral aciclovir is appropriate first-line therapy for immunocompetent patients without systemic symptoms.","Topical steroids should be avoided until after antiviral therapy has been established."],"references":["Kress DW. Pediatric dermatology emergencies. Curr Opin Pediatr. 2011;23(4):403-6. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/21670682/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90357"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1555"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"14833"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"14833","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/14833"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/452dcbb4-ee31-4d48-b1eb-acc0715a85eb.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/452dcbb4-ee31-4d48-b1eb-acc0715a85eb.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":640,"height":478}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90357","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/i